Lognormal race with unknown winner

Bruno Nicenboim

6/27/2019

set.seed(42)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
library(rstan)
rstan_options(auto_write = TRUE)
options(mc.cores = 3)

Im here trying to simulate the outcome of two processes, one is the time-out (to) that goes down according to the practice law, and another one proc that depends on a predictor X. The two processes follow lognormal distributions with the same variance, and the fastest one is the observed one. Importantly, I cant know directly which is the one that finished first in each trial.

N <- 5000
X <- rnorm(N)
Int_to <- log(1000) ##log(1000) = 6.9
Int_proc <- 6
r <- .0005
#effect of something:
mu_proc <- Int_proc + X *.1
#practice:
mu_to <- Int_to + -r*(1:N)
sigma <- .5
proc <- rlnorm(N,mu_proc,sigma)
to <- rlnorm(N,mu_to,sigma)
data <- tibble(trial=1:N,X, 
               proc=proc, 
               to=to, 
               RT = pmin(proc, to), 
               ## IRL, I don't know which one actually wins:
               winner_proc = proc< to)

It will look like this (the crosses are the observations):

data %>% gather(key="type",value="T", proc, to) %>%
    ggplot( aes(x=trial, y=T, color = type)) + geom_point(alpha=.5) +
    geom_point(aes(y=RT), size=2, color= "black", alpha=.1, shape =3)

This is the proportion of times proc won and was observed:

mean(proc < to)
## [1] 0.3792
mean(data$winner_proc)
## [1] 0.3792

Because these are two lognormal distributions, I can also calculate the proportions of the mixture like this, for every trial:

plnorm(1, mu_proc - mu_to, sqrt(2) * sigma) %>% head()
## [1] 0.8619605 0.9134336 0.8907047 0.8832578 0.8893450 0.9022580

And on average:

plnorm(1, mu_proc - mu_to, sqrt(2) * sigma) %>% mean()
## [1] 0.3760105

Stan model of the race (a lognormal race model with an unknown winner)

I try to fit this in stan with quite informative priors:

functions {
  // Stable approximation of the cdf that works better close to 0 and 1
  real lognormal_approx_cdf(real x, real mu, real sigma){
    real x_n = (log(x)-mu)/sigma;
    return inv_logit(0.07056 * x_n^3 + 1.5976* x_n);
  }
}
data {
  int N;
  vector<lower=0>[N] RT;
  vector[N] X;
  vector[N] trial;
}
parameters {
 real<lower=0> sigma;
  real Int_proc;
  real<lower= Int_proc> Int_to;
  real slope;
  real<lower=0> r;
}
transformed parameters{
  vector[N] mu_proc= Int_proc + X* slope;
  vector[N] mu_to = Int_to  - r* (trial/1000);
  vector[N] P_proc;
    //  given:
    // X ~ lognormal(mu_proc, sigma)
    // Y ~ lognormal(mu_to, sigma)
    // then:
    // X/Y ~ lognormal(mu_proc - mu_to, sqrt(2.0)* sigma)
    // X/Y < 1 => X was faster and was selected
    // P(X < Y) = lognormal_cdf(1, mu_proc - mu_to, sqrt(2.0)* sigma)
  for(n in 1:N)
     P_proc[n] = lognormal_approx_cdf(1.0,  mu_proc[n] - mu_to[n], sqrt(2.0)*sigma);
  //P_proc[n] = lognormal_cdf(1.0,  mu_proc[n] - mu_to[n], sqrt(2.0)*sigma);
}
model {
  // Quite informative priors:
  Int_proc~ normal(6,.1);
  Int_to ~ normal(log(1000),.1);
  slope ~ normal(.1,.3);
  r ~ lognormal(log(.5),.2);
  sigma ~ normal(.5,.5);
  // Likelihood:
  for (n in 1:N){
    target += log_mix(P_proc[n],  lognormal_lpdf(RT[n]|mu_proc[n],sigma),
                      lognormal_lpdf(RT[n]|mu_to[n],sigma) 
                      );
  }
}
generated quantities {
  real P_proc_avg = mean(P_proc);
  real RT_proc[N];
  real RT_to[N];
  real RT_gen[N];
  int winner_proc_gen[N];
  for(n in 1:N){
  RT_proc[n] = lognormal_rng(mu_proc[n],sigma);
  RT_to[n] = lognormal_rng(mu_to[n],sigma);
  // Generate fake data
  if(RT_proc[n] < RT_to[n]){
      winner_proc_gen[n] = 1;
      RT_gen[n] = RT_proc[n];
    } else {
      winner_proc_gen[n] = 0;
      RT_gen[n] = RT_to[n];
    }
  }
}
data_simple <- as.list(data) %>% c(N=nrow(data))
out_simple <- stan("race_proc.stan", data=data_simple, chains =6,iter=1000)

Stan model of a lognormal race model, assuming I know the winner (which I dont)

If I know which process is the fastest one, this is simply a lognormal race model, and its quite easy to fit:

functions {
  // Stable approximation of the cdf that works better close to 0 and 1
  real lognormal_approx_cdf(real x, real mu, real sigma){
    real x_n = (log(x)-mu)/sigma;
    return inv_logit(0.07056 * x_n^3 + 1.5976* x_n);
  }
}
data {
  int N;
  vector<lower=0>[N] RT;
  vector[N] X;
  vector[N] trial;
}
parameters {
 real<lower=0> sigma;
  real Int_proc;
  real<lower= Int_proc> Int_to;
  real slope;
  real<lower=0> r;
}
transformed parameters{
  vector[N] mu_proc= Int_proc + X* slope;
  vector[N] mu_to = Int_to  - r* (trial/1000);
  vector[N] P_proc;
    //  given:
    // X ~ lognormal(mu_proc, sigma)
    // Y ~ lognormal(mu_to, sigma)
    // then:
    // X/Y ~ lognormal(mu_proc - mu_to, sqrt(2.0)* sigma)
    // X/Y < 1 => X was faster and was selected
    // P(X < Y) = lognormal_cdf(1, mu_proc - mu_to, sqrt(2.0)* sigma)
  for(n in 1:N)
     P_proc[n] = lognormal_approx_cdf(1.0,  mu_proc[n] - mu_to[n], sqrt(2.0)*sigma);
  //P_proc[n] = lognormal_cdf(1.0,  mu_proc[n] - mu_to[n], sqrt(2.0)*sigma);
}
model {
  // Quite informative priors:
  Int_proc~ normal(6,1);
  Int_to ~ normal(log(1000),1);
  slope ~ normal(.1,.3);
  r ~ lognormal(log(.5),.2);
  sigma ~ normal(.5,.5);
  // Likelihood:
  for (n in 1:N){
    if(winner_proc[n]){
      target +=  lognormal_lpdf(RT[n]|mu_proc[n],sigma);
      target +=lognormal_lccdf(RT[n]|mu_to[n],sigma);
    } else {
      target += lognormal_lpdf(RT[n]|mu_to[n],sigma);
      target +=lognormal_lccdf(RT[n]|mu_proc[n],sigma); 
    }
  }
}
generated quantities {
  real P_proc_avg = mean(P_proc);
  real RT_proc[N];
  real RT_to[N];
  real RT_gen[N];
  int winner_proc_gen[N];
  for(n in 1:N){
  RT_proc[n] = lognormal_rng(mu_proc[n],sigma);
  RT_to[n] = lognormal_rng(mu_to[n],sigma);
  // Generate fake data
  if(RT_proc[n] < RT_to[n]){
      winner_proc_gen[n] = 1;
      RT_gen[n] = RT_proc[n];
    } else {
      winner_proc_gen[n] = 0;
      RT_gen[n] = RT_to[n];
    }
  }
}
data_simple <- as.list(data) %>% c(N=nrow(data))
out_simple_known <- stan("race_proc_known.stan", data=data_simple, chains =6,iter=1000)
